• DOMAIN: Automobile¶

• CONTEXT:¶

The data concerns city-cycle fuel consumption in miles per gallon to be predicted in terms of 3 multivalued discrete and 5 continuous attributes.

• DATA DESCRIPTION:¶

## cylinders: multi-valued

## time to accelerate from O to 60 mph (sec.) discrete acceleration: continuous

## engine displacement (cu. inches) displacement: continuous 

## model year (modulo 100) model year: multi-valued discrete

## horsepower: continuous 

## origin of car  origin: multi-valued discrete

## vehicle weight (lbs.) weight: continuous 

## car name: string (unique for each instance)

## MPG (miles per gallon) mpg: continuous

To understand K-means Clustering by applying on the Car Dataset to segment the cars into various categories.

Test Data:

On training data , support vector classifier without performing PCA has an accuracy score of 97 %

But when we applied the SVC model on PCA componenets(reduced dimensions) our model scored 81 %.

After PCA the model accuracy is droped from 97% to 81% training set and 92% to 82% for test set.

Considering that original dataframe had 18 dimensions and After PCA dimension reduced to 7, our model has droped in terms of accuracy score. </span>

#Finding optimal no. of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters=range(2,11)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(df_Car_z)
    prediction=model.predict(df_Car_z)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_Car_z, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df_Car_z.shape[0])

PART B | TOTAL | 30

DOMAIN: Automobile¶

CONTEXT:¶

The purpose is to classify a given silhouette as one of three types of vehicle, using a set of features extracted from the silhouette. The vehicle may be viewed from one of many different angles.

DATA DESCRIPTION:¶

The data contains features extracted from the silhouette of vehicles in different angles.

Four "Corgie" model vehicles were used for the experiment:

a double decker bus,

Cheverolet van, 

Saab 9000 and

an Opel Manta 400 cars.

This particular combination of vehicles was chosen with the expectation that the bus, van and either one of the cars would be readily distinguishable, but it would be more difficult to distinguish between the cars.

All the features are numeric i.e. geometric features extracted from the silhouette.

PROJECT OBJECTIVE:¶

Apply dimensionality reduction technique – PCA and train a model and compare relative results.

def transformation(df):
    df_nUnique = df.nunique()
    # Target columns
    target_col = ["class"]
    # categorical columns
    cat_cols = df_nUnique[df_nUnique < 10].keys().tolist()
    cat_cols = [x for x in cat_cols if x not in target_col]
    # numerical columns
    num_cols = [x for x in df_nUnique.keys() if x not in cat_cols + target_col]
    # Binary columns with 2 values
    bin_cols = df_nUnique[df_nUnique == 2].keys().tolist()
    # Columns more than 2 values
    multi_cols = [i for i in cat_cols if i not in bin_cols]

    print("Label encoding for Binary columns: ", bin_cols)
    # Label encoding Binary columns
    le = LabelEncoder()
    for i in bin_cols:
        df[i] = le.fit_transform(df[i])

    print("Label encoding for Target columns: ", target_col)
    # Label encoding Target columns
    le = LabelEncoder()
    for i in target_col:
        df[i] = le.fit_transform(df[i])

    print("\n")
    print("One Hot Encoding Multi Value columns ", multi_cols)
    # one Hot Encoding of columns for multi value columns
    df = pd.get_dummies(data=df, columns=multi_cols)


    return df

def ClassificationReport(model,X_train_scaled, X_test_scaled, y_train, y_test):
    #Predict the response for Training dataset
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_scaled)

    #Predict the response for test dataset
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

    # Training Set
    print("Training Set")
    print(classification_report(y_train, y_train_pred))

    # confusion matrix Training Set
    cm_Test = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_train_pred, labels=[0, 1,2])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm_Test,index=[i for i in ["bus", "car","van"]],
            columns=[i for i in ["bus", "car","van"]],
        )
    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt="g")
    plt.title("CONFUSION MATRIX : Training Data", fontsize=14)
    plt.show()

    # Test Set
    print("Test Set")
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))

    #confusion matrix Test Set
    cm_Test = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred, labels=[0, 1,2])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm_Test,index=[i for i in ["bus", "car","van"]],
            columns=[i for i in ["bus", "car","van"]],
        )
    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt="g")
    plt.title("CONFUSION MATRIX : Test Data", fontsize=14)
    plt.show()

xi = np.arange(1, 19, step=1)
yi = np.cumsum(pca_full.explained_variance_ratio_)

plt.ylim(0.0,1.1)
plt.plot(xi, yi, marker='o', linestyle='--', color='b')

plt.xlabel('Number of Components')
plt.xticks(np.arange(1, 19, step=1)) #change from 0-based array index to 1-based human-readable label
plt.ylabel('Cumulative variance (%)')
plt.title('The number of components needed to explain variance')

plt.axhline(y=0.95, color='r', linestyle='-')
plt.text(0.5, 0.85, '95% cut-off threshold', color = 'red', fontsize=16)

ax.grid(axis='x')
plt.show()

5. Data Understanding & Cleaning: [5 Marks]

A. Explain pre-requisite/assumptions of PCA. [2 Marks]¶

  • Always make sure data is normalized/scaled before perfroming PCA, else the result will not be as per expectations

  • Also it is recommended though it's not a rule , to split your data set into test-train before you apply data normalization/scaling. This will help our model to perfrom more realistically in production environment.

  • If one scale the model before splitting it into train-test , there is a high chance of data leakage . By data leakage i mean that our model will be alaready influenced by test data , as it has tasted a bit of test data even before it will fit and tested on it.

  • It is advisable to fine tune it using hyperparameter tuning techniques which tunes the model performances to make sure our model is ready to face production environment.

  • PCA data set impacts the model perfromance specially on training data set , we have here achived our objective and saw that PCA is great tool to make our model perfrom better . </span>

B. Explain advantages and limitations of PCA. [3 Marks]¶

Advantages of PCA

  • Removes the correlated attributes.

  • Help to reduce overfitting.

  • Improves the data visualization.

  • PCA helps in selecting relevant features by analysing the relationship between independent attributes to see which one will be more helpful in building our model without introducing any impurity in it

  • We can increase the models performance both in terms of processing speed and the ease of implementing it .

Disadvantages of PCA

  • Data normalization must be needed before applying PCA else the result will not be as per expectations

  • Some level of information loss.

  • Independent variables are become less interpretable.
